This not only confirms that some dinosaurs had feathers, a theory that is already popular, but shows details that fossils, as a rule, not visible, such as colors and three-dimensional arrangement.
Scientists say that the plumage of this animal was chestnut brown on top with a pale or a carotenoid color on the underside.
The discovery also provides insights into the development of feather development in birds.
Because dinosaur feathers do not have a well developed shaft called rachis, but have other functions for springs – mothooks and holsters – scientists assumed that rachis was probably a later evolutionary feature such as the other relevant features.
The structure of the feathers suggests that they were not used for flying but rather for temperature regulation or appearance.The researchers suggested that, even though this is the tail of a young dinosaur, the sample shows an adult, not a chicken, plumage.
