In France, voting rights have traditionally been a low-technological experience: voters go in alone in a booth a pre-printed sheet of paper indicating their candidate’s choice in an envelope.
After officials confirm the identity of the voter, the voter releases the envelope into the voice box and signs the voice call.
French electoral law has quite strict codification of the legal proceedings.
Since 1988, voice boxes must be transparent, so that voters and observers can testify that no envelopes are present at the start of voting and that no envelopes are added except for those carefully considered and from approved vote.
Candidates can send representatives to witness all parts of the process, and during the evening the votes are counted by volunteers according to specific procedures and under strict control.
